During school year 2017‒18, one- third of public schools (32 percent) reported assigning students based on their ability (



FIGURE 1



).

The percentage of schools assigning students based on ability showed no difference based on the percentage of K‒12 students approved for free or reduced-price lunches or the percentage minority enrollment in the school (



FIGURE 2



). The use of ability grouping across schools with different levels of students approved for free or reduced-price lunches ranged from 30 percent to 33 percent. Similarly, the use of ability grouping across schools with different levels of minority enrollment also ranged from 30 percent to 33 percent.
